bug.short_desc: Line delimiter settings are ignored during generating code

long_desc.thetext: I have set 'Unix' as Line delimiter in the preferences. When I generate the emf code this setting is ignored. This is a problem because when a larger team works on different platforms unnecessary code changes are generated because only of the line ending. Example: - * <!-- begin-user-doc --> - * <!-- end-user-doc --> + * <!-- begin-user-doc --> + * <!-- end-user-doc -->

I'll mark this as an enhancement request. We'll definitely try to address this in the 2.3 cycle. (It really should be possible even to match the nl convention of the target, but that wouldn't help the first time the file is generated.)

This occurs on OS X as well, as would be expected. This also occurs with GMF codegen. Could this be a JET issue? I'd like to vote for bug, not enhancement :) as it does pose significant issues in a cross-platform development team and this preference should be respected.

As the platform adds features (even ones we don't know about) we find ourselves having to play catch up. Unfortunately this isn't something that we can do trivially, so we'll need to have some time to get it done. I'll change it to a P1 priority to reflect the need for action.

Cool. Hope my comment wasn't snarky. Its an interesting reflection on the arbitrainess of so many software design decisions that *every* major OS uses a different one. (We deal with this issue all the time on a lot of contexts. Unfortunatly, svn does not handle this well. You can mark a file to force a given line-ending but then you have to do that for every new one. We'll probably just create an ant task to handle.)

Miles,
No problem. My skin has grown pretty thick over the years. I understand fully that a problem like this could be super annoying so you are merely expressing that natural reaction...

Would it make sense instead of using the user preferences to set it in the .genmodel because this makes sure that developers dont have to set the encoding explicitly? Because for example I store .ecore and .genmodel in subversion and as I can see this would be the only way that everyone uses the right line delimiter.

Marcus,
I'm not sure. We really need to explore this in detail. After all, if the rest of Eclipse is going to respect these settings, we really should too. In the end, the best approach is probably to try to match what's in the file if the file already exists...

I agree. Setting it exclusivly from .genmodel does not seem to follow the "principle of least surprise". I'm also not sure that follows the contract of the .genmodel. Not that an option would be a bad thing to have, e.g. "Platform; Unix, Mac, Windows", and perhaps for encoding as well, but I see this as a convience ala "Code Formatting".
Two asides..
1. Marcus' suggestion is recommended by the weak support for sharing of preferences across teams in Eclipse platform. I beleive there is a long outsrtanding and heavily commented bugzilla open on this, but in our project we end up having to constanatly remind submitters to set their platform settings correctly and consistently just for ordinary code.
2. This sort of undercuts my above argument ;), but ultimitly it would be nice to see the oAW work-flow or similar to support all of these common tasks we need to automate and perform consitently. Ultimitly things like platform-specific line-endings and so on should be pluggable and orthogonal to the representational concerns of .genmodel etc..

Here is some background email: David Dykstal/Rochester/IBM wrote on 11/15/2006 03:18:39 PM:

> ----- Forwarded by Violaine Batthish/Toronto/IBM on 11/15/06 01:18 PM ----- > > Buck Sent by: wdsci-l-bounces@midrange.com > > 11/15/06 09:54 AM > > Please respond to > Websphere Development Studio Client for iSeries <wdsci-l@midrange.com> > > To > > wdsci-l@midrange.com > > cc > > Subject > > [WDSCI-L] Connection as 'project' > > I listened in to the same webinar that Jeff did, and I admit I never > thought of a connexion as a 'project' before. All my connexions are > named for the physical machine they attach to. > > So I figure I really ought to get modern, and use a connexion as a > project, with its own filter pool and all that. Of course, the project > I'm working on now involves C source in PASE (the IFS) as well as RPG > members in OS400. I didn't see a way to put the filter for my IFS files > adjacent to the filter for my RPG members (they are segregated by > 'object' type (i.e. iSeries Object vs IFS files.) > > Is there a way to organise a project like this so that all the related > 'objects' are together under a single filter/pool? > --buck

This is an interesting enhancement request.
I think that in the end, we'll probably want to have very generic filters on EVERY level of RSE, even on the top-level (such that only particular hosts are selected; or, particular subsystems, from particular hosts are grouped together). I see two possible technical implementations:
(A) Static top-level filters (like working sets) ------------------------------------------------ The UI representation of these higher-level filters could be similar to the Working Sets in the Eclipse Resource Navigator -- allowing to select them either - as a view option (View-Menu > Select Working Set) or - as top-level elements (View-Menu > Top Level Elements > Working Sets).
Handling these top-level filters different than the lower-level filters would resolve issues of having nested filters, since the top-level filter would just be a shortcut to navigating to the lower-level filter but would not have any recursive impact on the lower-level filter.
(B) Dynamic top-level filters through a more generic filtering mechanism ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Bug 160113 proposes a generic filtering language that could apply to any type of remote objects. This generic filtering language would allow to define top-level filters that evaluate to any selection of objects from any host or subsystem.
The only problem I see with this is that it may be hard to find a proper UI represenation for the filter query creation dialog. Working Sets are much simpler in this respect.
--- Maybe a combined solution of (A) and (B) is best - representing the top-level filters graphically as working sets, but implementing them through a query language under the hood.

FYI, bug #182343 has a somewhat related request to create filters without having to select a context first (e.g. File > New > Filter...)
The problem with this is, that filters look extremely different depending on the subsystem they should act on. Therefore, such a request makes only sense with a generic filtering language.

bug.short_desc: [EFS] File system support in linked resources doesn't work

long_desc.thetext:
This is related to bug #124529.
Creating a link to an element in an external file system doesn't work.
Steps: * implement a non-"file:" file system * run a workbench with the file system plugin installed * create a new file, choose to link it to a file in the file system (via Advanced) * enter a URL matching your own file system scheme (e.g. ftp://...) * select your own file system from the dropdown * click finish
Expected: * the new file is an alias to a file in the selected file system Happens: * a defunct link is added
Investigation: WizardNewFileCreationPage has a method called createLinkTarget(), which uses URIUtil.toURI(String) to create the link target path. That is wrong for non-file: scheme files as it transforms URIs to nonsense (e.g. ftp://foo/bar gets something like "/ftp:/foo/bar"). So this will only ever work with the file: file system.
URIUtil should probably only be used if the user entered a direct path to a file, as opposed to a URI.
Martin, I think this is a duplicate of bug 137879, fixed in this week's integration build. Can you try the latest build and verify that it works for you?

I took me most of a day to download the Eclipse snapshot from that US server, but now I can confirm, it's fixed :-)
I'm resolving this as fixed as there is no "already fixed" state here.

bug.short_desc: Compile errors in build due to invalid class reference

long_desc.thetext: I added the use of a StringTokenizer to the CVSURI class in the org.eclipse.team.cvs.core plug-in. It turns out that ICU4J has a version of this class as well. When I was coding, I don't recall getting prompted to make the choice but somehow the ICU4J version was the one that got imported. This did not cause a problem in my workspace but the code did not compile during the build since the ICU4J class was not available to the CVS/Core plug-in. I think that the classpath of a plug-in in the workspace should match what is used during a build so that build breakages of this type can be avoided.

After talking with Michael, this appears to be a PDE Build issue. It looks like the tokenizer from the ICU4J plugin (com.ibm.icu.util.StringTokenizer) should resolve with the import-package statement from the cvs.core plugin's Manifest.
This is blocking nightly builds.

I have not been able to reproduce this. I checked out org.eclipse.team.cvs.core and modified CVSURI to import com.ibm.icu.util.StringTokenizer. When I looked at the classpath generated by pde.build, it correctly contained the com.ibm.icu jar and the build had no errors.
This happened a while ago so I don't remember much about it. Feel free to close it if you can't reproduce the error with the steps that were provided.

The Import-Package headers from the manifest must have been properly resolved during the build, otherwise it would have failed earlier on when generating scripts rather than reaching a compile error. com.ibm.icu should have been on the classpath.
The only things I can imagine having gone wrong are: 1) The manifest didn't acually import the com.ibm.icu packages. 2) Something was wrong with icu and the StringTokenizer wasn't there (? unlikely)

bug.short_desc: Provide support for untrusted security certificates for the log and sdb import from https URLs

long_desc.thetext: Currently log and sdb imports from https URLs support only trusted security certificates, i.e. a security certificate emitted by a certificate authority trusted by the version of Java Eclipse is running on. This is a limitation that needs to be addressed, support for self signed security cerificate should als be provided, in a similar way browsers are providing. If a security cerificate that is not one of the default ceriticates that Java supports is encountered, the UI should prompt the user whether he wants to accept the certificate. If the user chooses to accept the certificate it will be stored in a local workbench certificate store and used for establishing the https connection. The local certificate store should be used to check for certificates not found in the default java certificate store on each log or sdb import from an https URL.
Rough estimate: 40h.

bug.short_desc: 1.0.x J2EE module dependencies cannot be completely removed in 1.5

long_desc.thetext:
In 1.0.X, J2EE module dependencies were represented using entries in the following files:
.project .classpath .component MANIFEST.MF
(WEB-INF/lib dependencies where represented by .classpath and .component)
In 1.5, only a MANIFEST.MF reference is used for module dependencies and only a component file reference is used for WEB-INF/lib dependencies.
This means that when a user attempts to remove a 1.0.X dependency in a 1.5 workspace, stale references will be left (i.e. an explicit .classpath ref, etc.)
The module migrator logic will need to be enhanced to cover this use case (i.e. add the appropriate marker and, when executed, remove the now unused references).

long_desc.thetext:
One of the most common filters used in user assistance content (help topics, welcome pages, etc) is to filter based on whether or not a plugin is installed. This allows adding/modifying instructions based on which functionality is available, and provides links for product consumers to purchase tools or extensions to a product. bug.short_desc: Aggressive error generation while opening project/refreshing resources

long_desc.thetext:
The problem is that after some changes (in project files or structure) projects become completely unusable: Eclipse Runtime generates errors that are very hard to understand by users. For example, CoreException generated when project meta-information file objects (.project, .classpath etc.) contain inconsistent changes or dropped.
I'm plug-in developer ("Subversive" SVN Team Plugin for Eclipse Platform) and I processed many reports with the similar errors. At the moment, we have no chance to handle these exceptions in a user-friendly way and we performs some workaround steps in order to prevent the problems, but this workaround may significantly reduce performance in some cases and it sometime does not work.
Below you can find samples of the described behavior:
1) org.eclipse.core.runtime.CoreException: Error processing changed links in project description file. at org.eclipse.core.internal.resources.Project.open(Project.java:851) at org.eclipse.core.internal.resources.Project.open(Project.java:883) 2) org.eclipse.core.internal.resources.ResourceException: Errors occurred while refreshing resources with the local file system. at org.eclipse.core.internal.localstore.FileSystemResourceManager.refreshResource(FileSystemResourceManager.java:643) at org.eclipse.core.internal.localstore.FileSystemResourceManager.refresh(FileSystemResourceManager.java:627) at org.eclipse.core.internal.resources.Resource.refreshLocal(Resource.java:1244)
First exception prevents users from checking out the project from repository. Second one prevents plug-in from correct refreshing of resources after processing and next time (after described exception) users can take only "Out-of-sync with file system" exception when performing any changes in workspace.
So, I would like to propose my own solution for the problem: 1) provide callback interface for Eclipse Runtime, something like: public interface IResourceProblemInterceptor { public boolean handleError(Error identification data); } 2) provide public accessor which will allows to add interceptor instance to set of resource problem listeners 3) Eclipse Runtime will throws exception only if no interceptors returned "true". Interceptors should be called until any returns "true". 4) Eclipse UI (or any other subsystem in headless environment) should add its own interceptors which will provide user-friendly way for solving the problem. In simplest case this can be UI dialog with description (for Eclipse UI).

Just to be clear, you're not saying that these particular errors shouldn't be thrown, but that there be a way to handle errors in different ways?
I think something like this is already being done in Eclipse 3.3. See bug 154090 and bug 160303 for details.

I think in general exception shouldn't be generated if it is possible. You can see my opinion in details below...
The problem with exception generation is critical because workspace resources are unprotected from external changes. This mean that any resource presented in workspace can be unsafelly changed by some external process. In result of these changes resource become unusable. So, I think the problem will be solved if any operation over any erroneous resource completes successfully for the caller code. Most safe way to do this, from my point of view, is provide "interceptor-like" facility which will allows to recover from induced defects instead of exception throwing.
For example, what should be done if .project file is dropped and some code requested refresh operation for the project resources? At the current moment Eclipse IDE throws an exception which prevents user from working with the project. At the same time proposed solution will provide another way to handle the problem: When refresh operation is requested and .project deletion is detected inside Eclipse Runtime, problem interceptors should be called until someone handles problem in user-friendly way. The interceptor can be installed by UI should show to user dialog which describes situation and proposes recovery options. After user is selected interesting recovery option and pressed "Ok" button interceptor should perform recovery steps (restoring .project) and return "true". Thus Eclipse Runtime can safelly perform requested operation and no more exceptions required. In case if problem is not handled by interceptors Eclipse Runtime throws exception like earlier.
Perhaps the status handling in UI can help with this, but there is no plan to stop throwing these exceptions at the resources level.

bug.short_desc: JMerger: NPE when sorting an new field in the target

long_desc.thetext:
Scenario: 1. Source has fields 1, 2 and 3 marked with @ordered 2. Target has fields 2 and 1 (in this order)
Problem: In a first pass, JMerger will set the target to be 2, 3, 1 and in a second pass it will sort it as specified in the target. The AST facade implementation throws the following NPE when field 3 is removed by the sorting algorithm because LocationInParent is null for nodes that are added to a Compilation Unit.
java.lang.NullPointerException at org.eclipse.jdt.internal.core.dom.rewrite.RewriteEventStore.doMarkMovedAsRemoved(RewriteEventStore.java:775) at org.eclipse.jdt.internal.core.dom.rewrite.RewriteEventStore.prepareSingleNodeCopies(RewriteEventStore.java:768) at org.eclipse.jdt.internal.core.dom.rewrite.RewriteEventStore.prepareMovedNodes(RewriteEventStore.java:650) at org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.rewrite.ASTRewrite.internalRewriteAST(ASTRewrite.java:252) at org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.rewrite.ASTRewrite.rewriteAST(ASTRewrite.java:188) at org.eclipse.emf.codegen.merge.java.facade.ast.ASTJCompilationUnit.getContents(ASTJCompilationUnit.java:258) at org.eclipse.emf.codegen.merge.java.JMerger.getTargetCompilationUnitContents(JMerger.java:145) at org.eclipse.emf.codegen.ecore.generator.AbstractGeneratorAdapter.generateJava(AbstractGeneratorAdapter.java:958)

The fix for the NPE is to check if astNode.getParent() and astNode.getLocationInParent() return a not null value in ASTJType.remove(JNode).
This would fix the problem if it was not for the issue described in the bigzilla 164862 (ASTRewriter doesn't allows a code to remove a node recently added to the tree). As a workaround, we've extended the ASTRewriter to provide this feature.
The fix is committed to CVS.

bug.short_desc: swt.gtk.linux.x86 jar in org.eclipse.rcp feature needs a different environment combination for JWS on Suse 10

long_desc.thetext:
the org.eclipse.swt.gtk.linux.x86.jar library needs a second environment combination mapping for Suse 10.0. On Suse 10 the os.name and os.arch properties return the values "Linux" and "i386". The environment combination for the swt.gtk.linux.jar in the org.eclipse.rcp feature is only mapped for "Linux" and "x86". The mapping for the jar needs therefore a second mapping or the feature would need a second swt library for the i386 architecture(which is not really necessary, because it works fine with the gtk.linux.x86 library). If you export the feature for Java Web Start the needed mapping is missing and the library isn't downloaded on Linux machines with Suse 10. So you get the following Error:
org.osgi.framework.BundleException: The activator org.eclipse.ui.internal.WorkbenchPlugin for bundle org.eclipse.ui.workbench is invalid ... Root exception: java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: org/eclipse/swt/SWTError
You than have to add manually the resource block in the jnlp file of the rcp feature: <resources os="Linux" arch="i386"> <jar href="plugins/org.eclipse.swt.gtk.linux.x86_3.3.0.v3309.jar"/> </resources>
Together with the typo fixed in the Eclipse Web Start doc (bug 164875) this would have saved me a big headache deploying a rcp application with JWS on Linux. It took a while to find out why the application didn't start. I don't know if you can do much to fix this "bug", but at least you know now that this can be confusing for the users of the rcp-feature.
Not sure if this is the right component, but will start by moving to Platform Resources for comment.
I don't know much about how JWS works, but the class EclipseEnvironmentInfo does recognize "i386" and "Linux" and converts them to "x86" and "linux", so they should be equivalent. Pascal, any ideas?

In JWS we don't have the opportunity to do the same kind of transformation as in the EclipseEnvironmentInfo. Therefore the change has to be done in the code that generates the jnlp files (JNLPGenerator).
